# Autonomous directive — contingent on workflow & audits

When the user issues an **autonomous directive** (e.g. "go on autonomously", "execute Track A without asking", "only stop for decisions you cannot make"):

## Contingency (non-negotiable)

**The autonomous directive is contingent on our workflow and audits directive** — defined in [`docs/EXECUTION_TRACKS.md`](../../docs/EXECUTION_TRACKS.md). Autonomous mode does **not** bypass audits, gates, or Track B boundaries.

## When to ask the user

Ask **only** when a decision requires Track B: credentials, business/board approval, legal/tax path choice, production deploy approval, or information absent from docs and codebase.

## Required audits (every engagement)

1. **Pre-planning audit** — checkout **`main`** and pull; `npm run check`, `npm test`, read `EXECUTION_TRACKS.md` + relevant `MASTER_PLAN.md` sections; confirm work is Track A; map tasks to files. See [GIT_WORKFLOW.md](../../docs/GIT_WORKFLOW.md).
2. **Pre-implementation audit** — create branch from **`main`**; scope diff; risk check (migrations, live tables, breaking API); confirm no gated decision needed.
3. **Post-implementation impact assessment** — re-run `npm run check` + `npm test`; verify no unrelated regressions; document Track B env vars still unset; update `EXECUTION_TRACKS.md` engagement log.

## Execution

- Implement on a branch from **`main`** → commit → push → open a **draft PR with base `main`**.
- **Never merge your own PR** — the founder reviews and merges. `main` deploys to production on merge.
- Never base a PR on another unmerged PR's branch (stacked bases silently lose work when the parent merges first).
- Minimize scope; match existing conventions.
- Never skip audits to move faster.
